<TITLE> JS body for support to poultry </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, April 13 (bdnews24.com)--A parliamentary body has observed that the importing Indian eggs would hurt the local poultry industry. The committee on finance ministry made the observation after a meeting with poultry businessmen on Tuesday ahead of the national budget in June. A H M Mustafa Kamal, the committee chairman, told reporters that there should be a long-term poultry policy aimed at protecting the sector, which has an involvement of 50 lakh people. The commerce ministry recently awarded contracts to some companies to import 250 million eggs from India. The local poultry leaders criticised the decision. Kamal told reporters at the parliament's media centre that his opinion was that the government decision would hurt the local poultry industry. He said the poultry industry could generate 5 million more job opportunities if proper policy support was provided. Kamal was of the opinion that this labour intensive sector needed long-term policy support. "And that policy should not be changed from time to time." The committee chairman said the local poultry industry should get protection as the government had a plan to set up a farm at every house. Kamal said his committee also observed that the next budget should impose taxes on cancer medicine. "There is no duty on the cancer drugs, but the local companies must pay duty if they import raw materials to manufacture cancer medicine," said the chairman said. He said the local pharmaceuticals industry must be given policy support as they meet 90 percent of our local medicine demands. Finance minister A Maal Abdul Muhith did not attend the meeting. Kamal said the minister expressed his regrets for not turning up
